Stable Recursive Intelligence: A Geometric and Information-Theoretic Framework for Safe, Aligned Self-Improvement in Artificial General Intelligence

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

The prospect of self-improving artificial general intelligence (AGI) introduces a fundamental tension: recursive capability growth must be reconciled with alignment preservation, safety guarantees, and information-theoretic stability. This dissertation introduces the Stable Recursive Intelligence (SRI) framework, a mathematically rigorous model of continuous and discrete self-improvement dynamics constrained by geometric, informational, and control-theoretic principles. We formalize the Maakoul constraint, a requirement that mutual information between latent representations and rare environmental signals be non-decreasing throughout optimization, and prove that under five natural conditions—capability descent, Maakoul preservation, alignment invariance, verification-bounded updates, and control barrier safety—the resulting parameter trajectories exhibit monotonic capability growth, rare-signal retention, forward invariance of alignment subspaces, and strict safety. We bridge continuous flow dynamics to discrete stochastic updates, establishing supermartingale convergence and high-probability bounds on regressive proposals. This work positions SRI as the theoretical foundation for a new class of recursive alignment safeguards, connecting it to recent empirical systems such as SAHOO and Statistical Gödel Machines. We provide a rigorous analysis of mutual information estimation under rare-event sparsity and propose a benchmark for evaluating Maakoul constraint satisfaction. The framework is instantiated in a toy latent-space agent with a proposed experimental validation protocol. This work provides the first unified theorem-level guarantee for recursive AGI self-improvement and opens a rigorous pathway toward verifiable, scalable alignment.

